{{Orphan|date=January 2017}}
{{Infobox play | name = Khorshid Karevan {{Noitalic|(خورشید کاروان)}} | image = Khorshid_Karevan.jpg | image_size = | caption = Closing ceremony for the 2015 performance of in Tehran | writer = Mahdi Motevasseli | chorus = | characters = The Christian Monk, Petros, Zajr, Mokhaffar, The commander, The soldier, the kids (1 to 5) | mute = | setting = year 61 AH (<!--in [[Crescent Islamic calendar|AHc]]: October 9, and--> in [[Tabular Islamic calendar|AHt]]: 680 CE) in Levant | date of premiere = 1990 | original language = [[Persian language|Persian]] | series = | subject = Aftermath of [[Ashura]] | genre = Historical drama | web = }}
'''''Khorshid Karevan''''' ({{Lang-fa|خورشید کاروان}}) is an [[Iran]]ian play written by Mahdi Motevasseli from Fadak Cultural Institute<ref>{{cite web|title=Khorshid Karevan play - info|url=http://www.fadakci.com/Faalyatha/01_Khorshid.asp|website=www.fadakci.com|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref> played on scene for 26 consecutive years in Iran. The play has also been on scene in countries other than Iran including UK, UAE and the Netherlands. The popular religious theater in 2015 attracted 23000 spectators attending the performance in Tehran in [[Milad tower]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Closing ceremony of 2015 performance of Khorshid Karevan (English-translated title)|url=http://tn.ai/941377|website=Tasnim News Agency|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref> It has been estimated that more than a million spectators in total have seen the performance over the past 26 years.<ref>{{cite web|title=Senior players of Khorshid Karevan were recognized for their services (English-translated title)|url=http://tn.ai/940954|website=Tasnim News Agency|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref> The theater goes on scene in [[Muharram]] and [[Safar]] in memory of [[Ashura]] and its aftermath every year in Tehran and other cities in Iran.
Hossein Mosafer Astaneh and Mahmoud Farhang has been the first and the second directors of the play respectively.
==Cast== [[Anoushirvan Arjmand]] has been playing the role of the Christian Monk for 22 years until he died in 2014. [[Jalil Farjad]] replaced him in 2015. Keramat Roodsaz, Asadollah Babaii, Farhad BEsharati and Mahdi Amini are among the players for the last performance.<ref>{{cite web|title=Khorshid Karevan 25th year of performance (English-translated title)|url=http://www.nabteh.ir/Pages/News-%D8%A8%DB%8C%D8%B3%D8%AA_%D9%BE%D9%86%D8%AC%D9%85%DB%8C%D9%86_%D8%B3%D8%A7%D9%84_%D9%86%D9%85%D8%A7%DB%8C%D8%B4_%D8%AE%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%B4%DB%8C%D8%AF_%DA%A9%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%86_-9734.aspx|website=www.nabteh.ir|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref>
==Synopsis== A Christian Monk with his junior student (Petros) discuss the actual reference of the names "Ilia", "Shebr" and "Shobair" mentioned in the holy book in a remote, worn-out church outside Levant where the [[Caravan (travellers)|Caravan]] of [[Captives of Karbala]] along with Kufa army commander and soldiers reached the church. The soldiers discovers an ancient slate in the church that mentions the name of [[Husayn ibn Ali|Hussein]] and damned his murderers and think that the Christian Monk and his student are connected to [[Husayn ibn Ali|Hussein]] somehow and get ready to kill them. Hereafter the night at the church sees a lot of dramatic events and emotional episodes where the story of [[Ashura]] are being gradually told by the characters.<ref>{{cite web|title=Full text of the play - Persian language|url=http://www.fadakci.com/Faalyatha/Matn/01_Mtn_Khorshid.pdf|website=fadakci.com|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref>
==History of the play== The current form of play is inspired from the play named "Haiha't" written by Abu Basem Hayadaar.<ref>{{cite web|title=Khorshid Karevan play|url=https://www.gisoom.com/book/1719639/%DA%A9%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%A8-%D8%AE%D9%88%D8%B1%D8%B4%DB%8C%D8%AF-%DA%A9%D8%A7%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%86-%D8%A8%D8%B1-%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%A7%D8%B3-%D9%86%D9%85%D8%A7%DB%8C%D8%B4%D9%86%D8%A7%D9%85%D9%87-%D9%87%DB%8C%D9%87%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D8%AB%D8%B1-%D8%B2%D9%86%D8%AF%D9%87-%DB%8C%D8%A7%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D8%B3%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D8%A8%D9%88%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%85-%D8%AD%DB%8C%D8%A7%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%B1/|website=www.gisoom.com|accessdate=14 October 2016}}</ref>
